President Obama has announced his intent to nominate Janet L. LaBreck as Commissioner of the Rehabilitation Services Administration, Department of Education. LaBreck is currently the Commissioner of the Massachusetts Commission for the Blind and has been in that role since 2007. She has extensive experience in the field of rehabilitation services, including teaching courses in rehabilitation of the blind and case management at Assumption College. LaBreck holds a B.A. from the University of Massachusetts and an M.Ed. from Springfield College.

President Obama has also announced his intent to appoint Jonathan Safran Foer as a member of the United States Holocaust Memorial Council. Foer is a professor at New York University and an acclaimed author, best known for his books Extremely Loud and Incredibly Close and Everything is Illuminated. He has received several awards for his work, including the National Jewish Book Award and the Guardian First Book Award.

Robert Listenbee, Jr. has been appointed as the Administrator of the Office of Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention, Department of Justice. Listenbee has been Chief of the Juvenile Unit of the Defender Association of Philadelphia since 1997 and has extensive experience in juvenile justice. He serves on various policy committees and advisory boards related to juvenile justice and holds a B.A. from Harvard University and a J.D. from the University of California, Berkeley.

Dr. James Stock has been appointed as a member of the Council of Economic Advisors. He is currently the Chief Economist for the Council and has been in that role since 2012. Prior to joining the Council, Stock held various positions at Harvard University, including serving as the Harold Hitchings Burbank Professor of Political Economy. He has also served on several advisory boards and committees related to economics. Stock holds a B.S. from Yale University and an M.A. and Ph.D. from the University of California, Berkeley.